\begin{document}
\title{MetaMirror: A Metadata-First Safety Layer for AI Access to Local File Systems}

\author{Guanli Liu}
\affiliation{%
  \institution{The University of Melbourne}
  \city{Melbourne}
  \country{Australia}
}
\email{guanli.liu1@unimelb.edu.au}
\renewcommand{\shortauthors}{Liu}

\begin{abstract}
AI agents are increasingly deployed in local development and personal workspaces, where they can inspect, edit, move, and delete files. Existing harnesses mainly improve safety around direct file-system access by adding sandboxing, prompts, and checkpoints. We argue that this default is still misaligned with agent workloads: many tasks need semantic context, while raw file access grants coarse and destructive authority.

We propose \emph{MetaMirror}, a metadata-first safety layer that elevates a workspace-local metadata database into the default control plane for AI-file interaction. Agents operate on metadata, summaries, policy state, and derived artifacts by default; destructive raw-file operations are expressed as auditable proposals requiring approval and recoverable execution. This paper presents the architecture, synchronization model, AI gateway interface, and a workspace-local proof of concept with preliminary evidence. In our current results, MetaMirror blocks unauthorized destructive actions in safety scenarios, preserves proposal-based recoverability, and maintains high metadata consistency under randomized operation workloads. Our main vision claim is that metadata mediation should become a standard systems pattern for safe AI access to local files.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

