\subsection{Preliminary PoC Results}
Our current implementation provides early evidence for the vision, not a final end-to-end validation. In safety scenarios, the direct baseline produced unauthorized destructive effects (14 deletes and 7 overwrites), while MetaMirror reduced unauthorized deletes and overwrites to zero in the same setup, with 27 proposal creations and 13 recoverable soft-deletes. In consistency stress runs, the current benchmark reports per-operation consistency scores of 1.0 and aggregate proposal consistency near 0.98, with full audit completeness in the measured configuration.

In token-efficiency runs, metadata-context prompts reduced estimated context tokens by roughly 93--94\% relative to full-text context on the sampled workload. Robustness and transfer pilots add two additional signals: bounded staleness and near-zero duplicate proposals under bursty events, and stable safety/utility behavior across paper, code, and downloads workloads using one shared policy profile. The main tradeoff is higher approval latency on heterogeneous downloads folders.

Across repeated seeds in the current pilot harness, metric ordering is stable (MetaMirror vs. direct/sandboxed baselines) with low variance in safety and overhead trends. Overall, the evidence supports feasibility of metadata-first mediation across safety, utility, robustness, and governance dimensions; we intentionally present these findings as directional pilot evidence rather than large-scale final claims.

\subsection{Recoverability Metrics}
Recoverability experiments trigger deletion proposals and approved soft deletes, then measure restoration latency, audit completeness, and reversibility from local state.

\section{Open Challenges and Roadmap}
\subsection{Threat Model and Trust Assumptions}
MetaMirror assumes the agent accesses files through the MetaMirror gateway (CLI/MCP path) rather than unrestricted shell mutation. If unrestricted shell access is granted, policies can be bypassed; therefore MetaMirror should be combined with host controls such as sandboxing, restricted tool exposure, and protected paths.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Minimum secure deployment profile for MetaMirror.}
\label{tab:secure-profile}
\footnotesize
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{3pt}
\begin{tabular}{p{0.24\columnwidth}p{0.26\columnwidth}p{0.34\columnwidth}}
\toprule
Control Layer & Required Setting & Purpose \\
\midrule
Tool surface & MCP/CLI gateway only & prevent direct destructive bypass \\
Workspace scope & bounded project path allowlist & limit blast radius \\
Mutation policy & proposal-only for delete/overwrite/move & enforce human review boundary \\
Audit policy & append-only event/proposal log & support forensic reconstruction \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Why This Design Instead of Simpler Alternatives?}
Search indexes optimize retrieval, not safety mediation. Sandboxing constrains workspace boundaries, but does not by itself provide fine-grained proposal/audit control for high-risk operations. File-only metadata stores are possible in prototypes, but query-heavy policy and lifecycle reasoning is cleaner in a database-backed hybrid design (SQLite state, append-only audit logs, policy files, and derived artifacts).

\subsection{Limitations}
MetaMirror does not prevent all possible attacks. If an agent has unrestricted shell access to the raw workspace, it may bypass the gateway. Therefore MetaMirror should be combined with OS permissions, sandboxing, hooks, or MCP-only tool exposure. The PoC is workspace-local and does not protect the entire PC. It also relies on metadata freshness; stale metadata must be surfaced to the agent and user. Finally, metadata itself can be sensitive, so metadata visibility must also be policy-controlled.

\subsection{Future Research Roadmap}
Future work includes stronger MCP integrations, richer format-specific metadata extractors, vector search over approved summaries, broader multi-workspace deployment, and standardized benchmarks for AI-safe local file-system tasks.

\section{Conclusion}
This paper proposed MetaMirror, a metadata-first safety layer for AI access to local file systems. The core idea is to elevate the metadata database from a search or synchronization component into the default safety control plane between AI agents and local files.

MetaMirror continuously synchronizes a workspace into a local metadata database, exposes metadata and derived artifacts as the default AI-facing resources, and converts destructive raw-file operations into auditable, recoverable, human-approved proposals. This architecture preserves AI utility while reducing unnecessary raw-file access and preventing direct AI-driven deletion or overwrite.

As AI agents become common in local workspaces, we argue that metadata-first mediation should become a standard design pattern for safe personal computing.

